[Recorded Female Voice On Phone]
Thank you for your patience.

00:43.711 --> 00:47.046
Your call is important to us.
We will be with you shortly.

00:50.968 --> 00:54.595
[Chattering]

00:54.680 --> 00:58.015
Thank you for your patience.
Your call is important to us.

00:58.100 --> 01:00.351
We will be with you shortly.

01:06.191 --> 01:09.402
Thank you for your patience.
Your call is important to us.

01:09.486 --> 01:11.654
We will be with you shortly.

01:16.618 --> 01:19.829
Thank you for your patience.
Your call is important to us.

01:19.913 --> 01:21.873
We will be with you shortly.

01:21.957 --> 01:24.125
[Woman, Indian Accent]
Mrs. Greenslade,
thank you for waiting.

01:24.209 --> 01:25.710
I've consulted with my manager...

01:25.794 --> 01:28.463
Now if you'll just stay
on the phone for a moment
and talk to me.

01:28.589 --> 01:30.506
Just talk to me.
Of course.

01:30.591 --> 01:35.887
I'm not even clear- I mean,
I don't actually understand
what it is I'm trying to order.

01:35.971 --> 01:38.931
Is wireless the same as Wi-Fi?

01:39.016 --> 01:42.602
And what do either of them
have to do with broadband?

01:42.686 --> 01:45.688
Mrs. Greenslade,
since the account
is not in your name,

01:45.773 --> 01:47.732
before we can make
any changes,

01:47.816 --> 01:50.526
we need to verify details
with the account holder.

01:50.611 --> 01:53.237
Can I please speak
to the account holder?

01:53.322 --> 01:54.489
What?

01:54.573 --> 01:57.241
I'm asking if I can talk
to the account holder.

01:57.326 --> 01:59.285
Before we can make
any changes...

01:59.369 --> 02:01.162
You can't talk to him, no.

02:02.289 --> 02:03.790
He's dead.

02:04.625 --> 02:06.417
He died of a heart attack.

02:07.419 --> 02:09.086
There's only me.

02:09.170 --> 02:11.881
Mrs. Greenslade,
since the account
is not in your name...

02:11.965 --> 02:16.093
[Man]
Lord Justice Walton requests
the pleasure of our company.

02:16.178 --> 02:19.889
- Had you forgotten?
- I hate retirement parties.

02:19.973 --> 02:22.433
Crap cheese, crap wine.

02:22.518 --> 02:24.435
Endless speeches.

02:24.520 --> 02:26.395
Why do people do that?

02:26.480 --> 02:31.150
Nobody... Nobody ever said
about a retirement party,
you know,

02:31.235 --> 02:32.777
"Well, this is great.

02:32.861 --> 02:34.737
I can't wait to have
one of my own."

02:34.822 --> 02:36.364
It'll be yours one day.

02:36.448 --> 02:38.366
One day very soon.

02:38.492 --> 02:40.660
You've been saying that
for years.
[Chuckles]

02:40.744 --> 02:44.705
[Man] It was often said
of Stancombe that his bark
was worse than his bite.

02:44.790 --> 02:46.374
But as the recipient of both,

02:46.458 --> 02:51.254
I can testify to the fact
that neither actually
required surgery.

02:51.338 --> 02:52.588
[All Chuckle]

02:52.673 --> 02:56.050
His relationship with
all his pupils...

02:56.134 --> 02:58.052
was founded on respect.

02:58.136 --> 03:02.890
We respected him,
and he respected that.
[All Chuckle]

03:02.975 --> 03:06.894
Indeed, to this day,
I recall his response...

03:06.979 --> 03:09.647
to the unwelcome news
that I would trans...

03:09.731 --> 03:12.358
[Voice Fades]

03:12.442 --> 03:15.695
...praecipitium a tergo lupi.
[Echoing]

03:15.779 --> 03:18.030
[Al Laugh]

03:18.115 --> 03:19.615
This is the day.

03:20.784 --> 03:21.784
Graham?

03:25.247 --> 03:26.497
This is the day.

03:29.710 --> 03:32.128
[Beeping]

03:33.505 --> 03:35.715
And there's an unlimited range
of leisure opportunities...

03:35.799 --> 03:37.758
just a stone's throw away.

03:37.843 --> 03:42.221
So, as I say,
what you're looking at here
is very competitively priced.

03:42.306 --> 03:44.557
You won't see better
for your Grey Pound.

03:44.641 --> 03:46.309
Another little feature...

03:46.393 --> 03:48.895
not necessarily right now,
give it a few years...

03:48.979 --> 03:51.939
rails on the wall
to help you get around.

03:52.024 --> 03:54.942
And over here, a panic button.

03:55.027 --> 03:58.654
In case of a sudden fall,
brings the warden running.
[Chuckles]

03:59.740 --> 04:01.657
What if we fell
somewhere else?

04:01.742 --> 04:03.409
Sorry?

04:03.493 --> 04:05.786
It's just we might not manage
to plan our sudden fall...

04:05.913 --> 04:09.373
in the exact corner
where the button is.
Yeah, but-

04:09.458 --> 04:12.710
And would it be possible
to have the rail going through
the middle of the room...

04:12.836 --> 04:15.963
Darling.
To help us get across,
as well as around.

04:16.089 --> 04:18.925
Um, c-c-could we have
a moment, please? Thank you.
Yeah.

04:19.009 --> 04:20.927
Thank you so much.
[Door Opens]

04:21.970 --> 04:23.679
[Door Closes]
Darling...

04:23.764 --> 04:27.600
Thirty years
in the civil service,
and this is all we can afford.

04:27.684 --> 04:29.852
W-W-Would it help
if I apologize again?

04:29.937 --> 04:30.978
No.

04:32.940 --> 04:35.024
But try it anyway.

04:35.108 --> 04:39.153
[Woman On P.A.]
Could Dr. MacKenzie please
make his way to Theater 7.

04:39.237 --> 04:41.322
Dr. MacKenzie to Theater 7.

04:41.406 --> 04:44.784
Young lady, I want a cup of tea.
And I want it now.

04:44.868 --> 04:46.577
The trolley
will be along shortly.

04:46.662 --> 04:49.538
How hard do you have to fall
to get proper attention?

04:49.623 --> 04:51.082
I've been lying here for hours.

04:51.166 --> 04:52.917
Not a single doctor
has come to see me.

04:53.001 --> 04:55.461
Now that's not quite true,
is it, Mrs. Donnelly?

04:55.545 --> 04:58.839
A doctor did try
and examine you,
and you sent him away.

04:58.924 --> 05:03.052
What, that one?
He can wash all he likes.
That color's not coming out.

05:04.054 --> 05:06.013
I want an English doctor.

05:06.098 --> 05:08.057
Oh, an English doctor.

05:08.141 --> 05:10.893
Why didn't you say so?
I'll get one right away.

05:10.978 --> 05:12.436
Thank you.

05:16.024 --> 05:20.069
Mrs. Donnelly,
this is Dr. Ghujarapartidar.

05:20.988 --> 05:22.655
Notes, please.

05:24.908 --> 05:26.617
♪♪ [Hip-hop]

05:26.743 --> 05:29.328
[Man]
♪ Now here we go with the flow
of the girls you know ♪

05:29.413 --> 05:31.622
♪ The ones seen in Argentina
and Mexico ♪♪

05:31.748 --> 05:35.751
And after that,
I worked as a systems analyst
for a few years,

05:35.836 --> 05:38.629
but I just found it so dull.

05:38.714 --> 05:43.259
What I really wanted
was to do something
more creative that matched...

05:44.261 --> 05:45.845
Um, I'm sorry.

05:45.929 --> 05:50.349
Um, on the form,
they asked for
our age bracket...

05:50.434 --> 05:52.518
and the age
we wanted to meet.

05:52.602 --> 05:55.396
And in both cases,
I ticked "25 to 39."

05:55.480 --> 05:57.314
That's right. So did I.

05:57.399 --> 05:59.859
Anyway, don't stop. Uh...
"Something more creative."

05:59.985 --> 06:02.028
How old are you?
Early 40s.

06:02.112 --> 06:05.614
And, you know, my interests
are travel, theater-

06:05.699 --> 06:07.992
Do you mean you were born
in the early '40s?

06:08.076 --> 06:11.078
[Chuckles]
Judy, I know what you're asking.

06:11.163 --> 06:12.413
It's Judith.

06:12.497 --> 06:14.582
Judith. Trust me.

06:15.375 --> 06:17.043
I've still got it.

06:17.127 --> 06:19.003
[Bell Rings]

06:20.630 --> 06:22.715
Just can't find anyone
that wants it.

06:24.593 --> 06:27.470
Hi. I'm Norman.

06:27.554 --> 06:32.349
This is crazy. You're crazy.
You can't just up and leave like this.

06:32.434 --> 06:35.352
And yet, if you watch me,
that's exactly
what you'll see happen.

06:35.479 --> 06:37.021
What's going on?
Your mother's lost it.

06:37.105 --> 06:39.398
- My mother never had it.
- You talk to her.

06:39.524 --> 06:41.817
She doesn't listen to me.
Nobody listens to you.

06:41.902 --> 06:43.694
I still don't understand
what's going on.

06:43.779 --> 06:46.280
I just asked her to babysit,
and now she says she's leaving.

06:46.406 --> 06:48.783
But you love babysitting.
I loved it last night.

06:48.867 --> 06:50.743
We had pizza
and stayed up late.

06:50.827 --> 06:53.746
- And the night before?
- We had Chinese
and stayed up late.

06:53.830 --> 06:56.916
If you don't go,
tonight we could do a curry.

06:57.000 --> 07:00.294
It's tempting, darlings,
but you know I have to leave.

07:00.378 --> 07:01.504
We know.

07:01.588 --> 07:04.757
Being here is stopping her
finding a husband.

07:04.841 --> 07:05.966
Another one?

07:06.843 --> 07:08.552
Bye, Granny.
Bye, Granny.

07:08.637 --> 07:10.096
Don't let the buggers
get you down.

07:10.180 --> 07:12.389
How many husbands
have you had anyway?

07:12.474 --> 07:14.934
- Including my own?
- Mother.

07:15.018 --> 07:16.477
Mother.

07:17.229 --> 07:18.938
Mother!

07:19.022 --> 07:20.272
Thank you, yes.

07:21.858 --> 07:24.652
Right.
Name the place, darlin'.
Where you going?

07:26.822 --> 07:29.532
I've absolutely no idea.

07:30.242 --> 07:31.742
[Man Sighs]

07:31.827 --> 07:34.370
There's no other way.
There just isn't.

07:35.664 --> 07:37.373
Harold told us this
three months ago.

07:37.457 --> 07:39.458
And I'm afraid
matters have only got worse.

07:39.543 --> 07:41.293
We can't wait any longer.

07:41.378 --> 07:45.965
We need to put this flat
on the market and at least
start paying off Dad's debts.

07:46.049 --> 07:47.633
I've talked it through
with Polly and the boys.

07:47.717 --> 07:50.136
Of course, we all agreed.
Ma will come
and live with us.

07:51.221 --> 07:53.514
I think that's best, Evelyn.

07:54.641 --> 07:56.433
And it's what Hugh
would have wanted.

07:59.104 --> 08:01.939
Good. Well, that's settled.
End of discussion.

08:02.065 --> 08:04.650
Oh! That's just what
your father used to say...
Ma.

08:04.734 --> 08:06.777
When there'd never been
any discussion at all.

08:06.862 --> 08:08.487
I want to look after
things for you.

08:08.572 --> 08:12.241
What, like he did for 40 years?
Look how that turned out.

08:14.536 --> 08:18.372
How on earth do we know
what Hugh would have wanted?

08:18.456 --> 08:20.958
And would he have seen fit
to tell us anyway?

08:22.502 --> 08:24.795
Obviously,
the flat's got to be sold.

08:26.590 --> 08:30.050
And you're very kind,
and dear Polly.

08:30.135 --> 08:32.385
But I shan't be
coming to live with you.

08:33.513 --> 08:35.764
You need a new hip,
Mrs. Donnelly.

08:35.849 --> 08:37.725
It's not a difficult operation.

08:37.808 --> 08:41.061
That's easy for you to say.
You're not having it.

08:41.145 --> 08:43.522
Regardless.
You do need a new hip.

08:43.607 --> 08:46.442
- I'm not gettin' it from you.
- Not me personally, no.

08:46.526 --> 08:49.612
- No, none of your lot.
- I see.

08:49.696 --> 08:51.197
When do I have the operation?

08:51.281 --> 08:53.866
I'm afraid you'll be
on the waiting list
for at least six months.

08:53.950 --> 08:56.952
At my age,
I can't plan that far ahead.

08:57.037 --> 08:59.455
I don't even buy green bananas.

08:59.539 --> 09:02.750
There is another way.

09:02.834 --> 09:05.377
Our hospital trust is funding
a pilot scheme...

09:05.462 --> 09:08.255
that will enable us
to outsource you
to another hospital...

09:08.340 --> 09:11.175
where they can
perform the procedure
almost immediately...

09:11.259 --> 09:12.968
and at a fraction of the cost.

09:13.053 --> 09:14.470
Is it local?

09:16.097 --> 09:19.266
[Evelyn On Phone]
They cover the cost
of the flight out apparently.

09:19.351 --> 09:21.560
When did you get a computer?

09:21.645 --> 09:23.771
How far along
is the progress bar?

09:23.897 --> 09:26.982
That thing at the top.
It tells you...
I know what it is, Ma.

09:27.067 --> 09:28.859
What are you
showing me anyway?

09:28.985 --> 09:33.822
[Man, Indian Accent]
Come and spend your autumn years
in an Indian palace...

09:33.907 --> 09:38.077
with the sophistication
of an English country manor.

09:38.161 --> 09:42.248
Tucked away on the outskirts
of Jaipur, and graced with
breathtaking surroundings...

09:42.332 --> 09:45.376
[Jean]
"Lofty terraces,
open courtyards,

09:45.460 --> 09:47.753
domes, arches...

09:47.837 --> 09:51.966
and canopied balconies
abound with opulent comfort.

09:52.050 --> 09:56.178
Indeed, the entire building
exudes historical ambience...

09:56.263 --> 10:02.184
and transports one
back in time to the proud
tradition of the Raj."

10:02.268 --> 10:04.853
Is that good?
It is. It is.

10:04.938 --> 10:08.357
Very good.

10:09.985 --> 10:13.946
Thirty-six years,
four months since the day
we were called to the bar,

10:14.030 --> 10:16.198
and you've never once
talked about India.

10:16.282 --> 10:18.242
Do you want
any of these books?

10:18.368 --> 10:20.494
You might be
needing them again.
[Chuckles]

10:20.620 --> 10:23.330
Mrs. Megson.
[Woman]
Sir?

10:23.415 --> 10:24.748
I want you to have this.

10:25.792 --> 10:27.251
Are you sure?
Oh, absolutely.

10:27.335 --> 10:29.795
Th-There's a little crack there
just on the bottom,

10:29.879 --> 10:32.047
but I think you know something
about that already.

10:34.759 --> 10:36.427
I used to live there...

10:38.763 --> 10:40.472
a long time ago.

10:44.185 --> 10:46.353
There won't be
any golf courses.

10:46.438 --> 10:49.273
Well, that's just as well.
I can't afford the green fees.

10:49.357 --> 10:50.899
But a retirement home?

10:50.984 --> 10:52.651
It's a luxury development...

10:52.736 --> 10:55.195
where all the residents
are in their golden years.

10:55.280 --> 10:56.905
Like the Costa Brava?

10:56.990 --> 11:00.242
Yeah, but with more elephants.

11:02.746 --> 11:04.413
[Sighs]

11:05.707 --> 11:09.001
[Muriel]
You know who'll be there...
Indians.

11:09.085 --> 11:10.836
Loads of them.

11:10.920 --> 11:13.547
Brown faces and black hearts.

11:13.631 --> 11:16.425
Reeking of curry.

11:16.509 --> 11:18.886
And you never see one
on their own, do you?

11:18.970 --> 11:21.221
I mean, they always...
they move in packs.

11:21.306 --> 11:24.224
Makes it easier
to rob you blind,
cut your throat.

11:24.309 --> 11:27.519
You know what?
You can wheel yourself
from here.

11:29.105 --> 11:31.315
You're supposed to
take me to my flat.

11:31.399 --> 11:33.776
My wife's from Mumbai.

11:33.860 --> 11:36.653
Well, don't blame me, mate.
You married her.

11:38.198 --> 11:40.032
"My wife's from Mumbai."

11:40.116 --> 11:43.285
[Airplane Engine Roaring]

11:45.997 --> 11:49.458
Has anyone thought
about what happens
when you get to the other end?

11:49.542 --> 11:52.044
[Evelyn]
They said somebody's
going to meet us in Jaipur.

11:53.296 --> 11:55.130
How are we going to know
you're all right?

11:55.215 --> 11:58.926
Well, I'll call.
They do have phones
there, you know.

11:59.052 --> 12:01.470
Or you can read my blog.
Your what?

12:01.554 --> 12:03.055
On the Interweb.

12:03.139 --> 12:05.641
Just log in
whenever you like
and read my news.

12:05.725 --> 12:08.352
Well, I hope the first item
will be announcing your return.

12:08.436 --> 12:10.395
I don't suppose
they'll be paying
for the journey back.

12:10.480 --> 12:15.192
Look, before I go,
I wonder, could you say
one thing that's supportive?

12:15.276 --> 12:18.987
I've never done
anything like this
in the whole of my life.

12:19.072 --> 12:21.240
You've never done
anything at all without Dad.

12:22.450 --> 12:24.660
I don't think
you'll be able to cope.
Well,

12:24.744 --> 12:26.703
let's just find out,
shall we?

12:29.499 --> 12:32.543
And the connecting flight
to Jaipur
is first class too?

12:32.627 --> 12:33.710
That's right.

12:33.795 --> 12:35.963
I tell you. It's tough
to get upgraded nowadays.

12:36.047 --> 12:38.340
I had to flirt so hard
with the travel agent,

12:38.424 --> 12:40.551
it was practically
phone sex.

12:47.183 --> 12:48.517
[Beeps]
Oh.

12:50.270 --> 12:53.230
Well, this is my lucky day.

12:53.314 --> 12:54.815
Sir.

12:57.277 --> 13:00.279
[Man] We'd like to
take a look in this bag,
madam, if you don't mind.

13:00.363 --> 13:02.447
[Scoffs]
What have you got
in here anyway?

13:02.532 --> 13:04.408
It's just PG Tips.

13:05.368 --> 13:06.827
And some brown sauce.

13:06.911 --> 13:09.955
Thirty-one packets
of chocolate Hobnobs.

13:10.039 --> 13:11.540
[Clears Throat]

13:11.624 --> 13:15.669
That's pickled onions
and, yeah, pickled eggs.

13:15.753 --> 13:17.796
And that's just pickles.
Pickles.

13:17.881 --> 13:20.716
- [Sighs]
No liquids on the plane.
- What's that mean?

13:20.800 --> 13:23.385
It means you can't take
the pickled onions...

13:23.469 --> 13:25.220
or the pickled eggs.

13:26.139 --> 13:27.890
[Exhales]
The pickles fine.

13:27.974 --> 13:29.433
Oh!

13:34.397 --> 13:37.941
[Man Speaking On P.A.,
Indistinct]

14:28.868 --> 14:30.953
[Jean]
Obviously,
one has read one's Kipling,

14:31.037 --> 14:34.998
but we view this as
an opportunity to explore
another culture,

14:35.083 --> 14:36.583
as well as making
new friends.

14:36.668 --> 14:41.004
And a High Court judge
is just the class of guest
one was hoping for.

14:41.089 --> 14:43.298
[Chuckles]
Isn't it, Douglas?

14:43.383 --> 14:44.591
Sorry?

14:44.717 --> 14:48.053
And, um, is this
your first time in India?
Yes.

14:48.137 --> 14:49.846
You don't look like
an experienced traveler.

14:49.931 --> 14:51.807
Oh, I'm not.

14:51.891 --> 14:54.768
But one has read
one's guidebooks.
[Chuckles]

14:54.894 --> 14:56.979
It should be there.
No.

14:57.063 --> 14:58.397
Oh.

14:58.481 --> 14:59.773
Oh. Hi.

14:59.857 --> 15:02.734
Hello. We haven't met.
Norman Cousins.

15:02.819 --> 15:04.820
Madge Hardcastle.
A pleasure.

15:04.904 --> 15:06.822
Play your cards right,
and it could be.

15:06.948 --> 15:10.033
Look. My chair.
What? Oh, yes, yes.
Hang on.

15:10.118 --> 15:12.035
[Woman On P.A.]
May I have your attention,
please?

15:12.120 --> 15:15.998
We regret to announce
cancellation
of Flight 105 to Jaipur,

15:16.082 --> 15:18.917
owing to bad weather
at the destination.

15:19.002 --> 15:21.503
We apologize
for any inconvenience caused.

15:29.929 --> 15:31.096
Right.

15:31.180 --> 15:32.889
[Jean]
Of course it's a good idea.

15:32.974 --> 15:35.767
Who can one trust
if not a High Court judge?

15:35.852 --> 15:38.061
I suppose this way
we see more of the country.

15:38.146 --> 15:40.522
If anyone asks,
say you're my mother.

15:40.606 --> 15:42.816
I don't want people
to think we're together.

15:42.900 --> 15:44.568
In your dreams.

15:44.652 --> 15:46.820
Douglas, these are not words
that often pass my lips,

15:46.904 --> 15:49.197
but you may actually
be right.

15:49.282 --> 15:53.076
This country seems
rather more civilized
than one originally thought.

15:53.161 --> 15:55.495
[Whistles Blowing]
[Loud Chattering]

16:02.170 --> 16:04.546
Okay. Thank you.

16:08.718 --> 16:13.430
The bus... The bus will take us
to the center of the town,

16:13.514 --> 16:15.891
and then we can get tuk-tuks
the rest of the way.

16:16.017 --> 16:18.560
[Muriel] What did he say?
So it's down there.
Yeah, it's down there.

16:20.021 --> 16:21.813
Down here. The yellow one.
That one.

16:21.898 --> 16:23.398
[Madge]
But look at the bus!

16:23.483 --> 16:26.610
There's not enough room!

16:26.694 --> 16:29.571
First rule of India...
"There's always room."

16:32.450 --> 16:33.950
There we are.

16:34.035 --> 16:35.577
Ah.

16:35.661 --> 16:36.703
Sorry.

16:36.829 --> 16:38.830
In you go.
"What larks, Pip!"
[Chuckles]

16:38.915 --> 16:41.291
Well, let's hope so.

17:09.028 --> 17:12.239
[Horn Honking]

17:15.576 --> 17:18.619
- Oh!
- [Screams]

17:18.704 --> 17:20.288
[Screaming]

17:23.667 --> 17:26.752
Oh!
[Laughs]

17:26.838 --> 17:28.713
I'm really
loving this.

17:28.798 --> 17:30.340
[Laughing]

17:32.885 --> 17:34.845
Oh. Thank you.

17:40.601 --> 17:42.477
Are you insane?

17:42.562 --> 17:45.605
Avoid all food
not from a reputable vendor.

17:45.690 --> 17:47.899
It'll be washed
in impure water.

17:47.984 --> 17:49.943
It's just a sandwich.

17:50.027 --> 17:53.155
Oh, marvelous.
Then I'll have ham,
cheese and streptococcus.

17:54.323 --> 17:57.242
Or perhaps bacteria,
lettuce and tomato.

17:57.326 --> 17:58.618
Huh.

17:58.703 --> 18:00.620
Would you like some of this?

18:00.705 --> 18:04.166
I believe it's called
aloo ka paratha.

18:04.250 --> 18:07.586
No, if I can't pronounce it,
I don't want to eat it.

18:11.549 --> 18:13.967
♪♪ [Indian Folk Pop]

18:16.220 --> 18:18.930
♪♪ [Woman Singing
In Indian Language]

18:33.070 --> 18:35.280
♪♪ [Man Vocalizing]

18:43.498 --> 18:45.081
[Evelyn]
How long
since you've been here?

18:45.166 --> 18:46.917
Forty years.

18:47.001 --> 18:48.084
Oh.
[Chuckles]

18:48.169 --> 18:50.045
That's as long
as I was married.

18:50.963 --> 18:53.340
My husband died recently.

18:53.424 --> 18:54.925
Oh, I'm sorry.

18:58.596 --> 19:00.514
Do you think
we'll be all right?

19:00.598 --> 19:02.057
God, don't ask me.

19:02.183 --> 19:04.476
I'm more scared
than you are.
Oh.

19:04.560 --> 19:07.020
♪♪ [Continues]

19:07.104 --> 19:09.064
No.

19:09.148 --> 19:11.107
It's going to be
extraordinary.

19:17.198 --> 19:19.282
[Evelyn]
What exactly is a tuk-tuk?

19:32.463 --> 19:34.464
Oh, look! What's that? Look!

19:40.513 --> 19:42.097
Oh!

19:44.100 --> 19:45.433
[Moos]

19:46.310 --> 19:47.310
Ah!
[Laughs]

20:00.783 --> 20:02.909
[Chattering]

20:10.167 --> 20:12.627
[Jean]
Is this it?

20:12.712 --> 20:14.629
[Douglas]
Well...
[Stammers]

20:20.177 --> 20:23.263
[Bell Ringing]
[Men Chattering]

20:23.347 --> 20:24.889
[Speaking Indian Language]

20:27.184 --> 20:29.436
[Chattering Excitedly]

20:30.479 --> 20:32.355
Here! Watch it!
Sorry.

20:53.127 --> 20:57.047
Welcome
to The Best Exotic
Marigold Hotel!

21:12.897 --> 21:14.522
Oh!

21:24.492 --> 21:26.201
[Whispers]
There's an Indian in there.

21:26.285 --> 21:28.203
[Chuckles]

21:37.129 --> 21:38.630
Ah.

21:44.595 --> 21:46.596
[Sighs]

21:46.681 --> 21:48.890
This will do.

21:53.771 --> 21:55.730
Bird in room.

21:58.526 --> 21:59.734
[Gasps]

22:02.655 --> 22:05.532
[Manager]
This is a building
of the utmost character,

22:05.616 --> 22:09.202
which means that perhaps
not everything will function
in the way you expect it to.

22:09.286 --> 22:10.954
But, as the manager...

22:11.038 --> 22:13.623
and chief executive
supervising officer
of this Marigold Hotel,

22:13.708 --> 22:17.460
I can tell you with great pride
that the building
has stood for centuries...

22:17.545 --> 22:22.590
and will continue to stand
for many more
in 100% shipshape condition.

22:22.675 --> 22:24.884
Please follow me,
carefully avoiding
that naughty stone there.

22:24.969 --> 22:26.886
[Chuckles]
Around this corner,

22:26.971 --> 22:29.139
leading us most successfully
all the way to...

22:29.223 --> 22:30.974
your bedroom.

22:31.684 --> 22:33.476
Where?

22:33.561 --> 22:35.729
Here. In here.

22:35.813 --> 22:38.648
My dear man,
rooms have doors.

22:38.733 --> 22:40.942
What you're showing me here
is an alcove.

22:41.026 --> 22:43.528
A door is coming soon,
most definitely.

22:43.612 --> 22:44.988
How soon?

22:45.072 --> 22:48.366
Let us not concern ourselves
with details, Mrs. Hardcastle.

22:48.451 --> 22:50.076
Rather than speaking
of doors,

22:50.161 --> 22:52.912
we should instead take pleasure
in the freedom to roam.

22:53.038 --> 22:55.165
Does your room have a door?
A most effective one.

22:55.249 --> 22:58.293
Good. Then that's
where I'll be staying.

23:00.463 --> 23:02.380
[Man]
You will be coming
to the hospital...

23:02.465 --> 23:05.341
once you're satisfactorily
recovered from your journey.

23:07.219 --> 23:12.515
The operation requires
a stay of five days, and it is done
under general anesthesia.

23:12.600 --> 23:16.352
A hip replacement
usually takes
only two hours.

23:16.437 --> 23:19.481
Your surgeon will remove
the top end of the thighbone...

23:19.565 --> 23:22.692
and insert
an artificial bone instead.

23:22.777 --> 23:24.903
A most routine procedure.

23:24.987 --> 23:27.113
Have you got
a marker pen on you?

23:27.198 --> 23:28.448
Why?

23:28.532 --> 23:29.991
I want to mark it.

23:30.075 --> 23:32.327
I don't want you
to do the wrong hip.

23:32.411 --> 23:33.912
[Dings]

23:33.996 --> 23:38.249
I want to stay
at the other hotel,
the one that's in the brochure.

23:38.334 --> 23:40.794
Mrs. Ainslie,
prepare to be amazed.

23:40.878 --> 23:42.921
This is that very building,
madam.

23:43.005 --> 23:44.589
You Photoshopped it!

23:44.673 --> 23:47.217
No. I have offered a vision
of the future.

23:47.301 --> 23:49.761
Of course,
I'd hoped that by now
it would be the present.

23:49.845 --> 23:52.305
But, you know, in India,
we have a saying...

23:52.389 --> 23:54.682
"Everything will be
all right in the end."

23:54.767 --> 23:57.310
So if it is not all right,
it is not yet the end.

23:57.394 --> 24:00.313
What will start
to make it all right
is if you'll give us a refund.

24:00.397 --> 24:03.316
Of course. Of course.
If that is what you desire,
then you must have it.

24:03.400 --> 24:06.069
- Absolutely no problem.
I'll refund you completely.
- [Bell Dings]

24:06.195 --> 24:07.987
You will?
Most definitely, madam.

24:08.113 --> 24:10.031
Straightaway?
I most definitely will.

24:10.115 --> 24:12.075
Straightaway
in three months, okay?

24:12.159 --> 24:17.121
Um, have you tried, um,
jiggling it about a bit?

24:17.206 --> 24:18.915
Yes, I did that.

24:18.999 --> 24:23.670
Did you kind of
bang it lightly
on the desk a few times?

24:23.754 --> 24:25.505
Yes, I did that too.

24:25.589 --> 24:27.882
Okay. Um...

24:32.429 --> 24:33.680
Right.

24:39.103 --> 24:41.271
How do you come
to be in India?

24:41.355 --> 24:42.939
Oh, uh... Oh.

24:43.023 --> 24:46.317
I invested our...
well, my retirement money...

24:46.402 --> 24:49.404
in our daughter's
Internet company.

24:49.488 --> 24:55.076
She assured me
that as soon as the start-up
actually, uh, started up...

24:55.160 --> 25:00.456
and the conversion
from virtual to actual
became sufficiently viable,

25:00.541 --> 25:03.084
then she'd be able
to pay it all back.
[Blows]

25:03.168 --> 25:05.670
I'm not sure I understand
what most of those words mean.

25:05.754 --> 25:09.132
Well, it turns out
neither did she.

25:09.216 --> 25:12.051
Ah. There you are.
Good as new.

25:12.177 --> 25:13.845
Really?
No, of course not.

25:13.929 --> 25:15.972
[Laughs]

25:19.101 --> 25:22.562
Now, would you like me
to, um, not fix that chair?

25:22.646 --> 25:24.606
Because I could
almost certainly
do that as well.

25:25.566 --> 25:27.734
[Squawking]

25:29.945 --> 25:31.779
♪♪ [Indian Traditional]

25:31.864 --> 25:34.657
[Manager]
How long have I waited
for this moment...

25:34.742 --> 25:38.578
to present to you,
in honor of your arrival,

25:38.662 --> 25:41.956
a special
"Welcome British" roast
for you all.

25:42.917 --> 25:44.751
Cooked lovingly by myself...

25:44.835 --> 25:47.962
and my most loyalist helper
and friend, Young Wasim.

25:48.047 --> 25:50.840
- Roast what?
- A wonderful taste of Blighty.

25:50.925 --> 25:52.842
Roast what?

25:52.927 --> 25:54.761
Roast goat curry.

25:54.845 --> 25:58.306
Gentle friends, you have found
your way to this place,

25:58.390 --> 26:01.225
bequeathed to me
by my beloved father,

26:01.310 --> 26:04.395
that I have raised
from the ruins
of his broken dreams...

26:04.480 --> 26:08.107
and renamed The Best
Exotic Marigold Hotel...

26:08.192 --> 26:11.819
for the Elderly and Beautiful.

26:11.904 --> 26:15.823
Yes. I use these words
most deliberately.

26:15.908 --> 26:18.952
For you have all heard
the chimes at midnight,

26:19.036 --> 26:21.204
and long in tooth
have you become.

26:22.623 --> 26:24.874
Who knows how many days
you have left?

26:24.959 --> 26:29.212
But we are most honored
that you have chosen
to spend that time with us.

26:29.296 --> 26:30.380
Please...

26:30.464 --> 26:32.090
- [Madge]
Oh!
- [All Gasping]

26:32.216 --> 26:34.092
[Muriel]
What's he got?
Douglas, do something.

26:34.176 --> 26:36.344
Let me through, please.
My brother is a doctor.

26:36.428 --> 26:37.887
Sorry, please.

26:47.856 --> 26:49.607
This man is dead.
Oh, my God!

26:49.733 --> 26:53.778
Please, we must cover his face.
We should preserve his dignity
at this terrible moment.

26:59.910 --> 27:01.494
I'm sorry, buddy.

27:03.872 --> 27:04.914
[Coughs]

27:04.999 --> 27:06.708
- He coughed. I saw him cough.
- He moved.

27:06.792 --> 27:07.709
He's alive.

27:13.007 --> 27:15.008
Did... Did I nod off?

27:15.092 --> 27:16.843
[All Laughing]

27:16.927 --> 27:19.637
All is right. He didn't die.

27:21.724 --> 27:24.225
[Norman] I was
looking forward to that meal.
[Muriel] It's hell.

27:24.351 --> 27:26.561
[Jean]
I was frightened.
I'm in hell.

27:29.440 --> 27:31.482
[Squawking]

27:35.362 --> 27:39.949
[Evelyn Narrating]
Marigold Hotel, Jaipur.
Day nine.

27:40.034 --> 27:45.288
Old habits die easier
than we think,
and new ones form.

27:45.372 --> 27:48.708
No longer do I reach out
in the morning for Radio 4.

27:48.792 --> 27:52.086
My news comes instead
from the Jaipur Herald.

27:52.171 --> 27:54.005
[Horns Honking]

27:54.089 --> 27:59.761
Soon, I might even
grow accustomed to the storm
of car horns and vendors.

28:00.262 --> 28:01.637
One moment.

28:02.848 --> 28:04.807
The carburetor, sir.
Carburetor is broken.

28:04.892 --> 28:07.435
Can there be anywhere else
in the world...

28:07.519 --> 28:10.480
that is such an assault
on the senses?

28:12.316 --> 28:14.650
[Phone Rings]
[Chattering]

28:14.735 --> 28:18.279
Those who know
the country of old
just go about their business.

28:20.449 --> 28:24.035
But nothing can prepare
the uninitiated...

28:24.119 --> 28:27.038
for this riot
of noise and color,

28:27.122 --> 28:29.248
for the heat, the motion,

28:30.042 --> 28:32.794
the perpetual teeming crowds.

28:32.878 --> 28:35.296
[Horns Honking]

28:36.757 --> 28:40.134
Sonny is conducting
his own personal assault
on our senses...

28:40.219 --> 28:43.930
with a flow of exotic dishes
he demands daily
from the kitchen.

28:45.933 --> 28:47.725
Mooli moong dal,

28:47.810 --> 28:49.685
bagara baingan,

28:49.770 --> 28:51.813
banjara gosht,

28:51.897 --> 28:53.648
paneer methi chaman,

28:53.732 --> 28:55.817
mutton vindaloo.

28:56.860 --> 28:59.445
[Water Running]

29:02.991 --> 29:04.992
Initially, you're overwhelmed.

29:06.870 --> 29:09.622
But gradually,
you realize it's like a wave.

29:10.749 --> 29:13.042
Resist
and you'll be knocked over.

29:13.127 --> 29:14.168
Mrs. Donnelly!

29:16.421 --> 29:20.508
Dive into it,
and you'll swim out
the other side.

29:24.847 --> 29:28.432
Excuse me.
I wonder, could you
direct me to this address?

29:28.517 --> 29:30.017
[Indian Language]

29:30.102 --> 29:32.812
No more. No more.
I don't have any more.

29:32.896 --> 29:34.522
[Chattering]
I haven't got any more.

29:34.606 --> 29:36.566
This is a new
and different world.

29:37.568 --> 29:39.235
The challenge
is to cope with it.

29:41.280 --> 29:44.740
And not just cope, but thrive.

29:50.539 --> 29:53.166
Graham was talking about
this marvelous temple.

29:53.250 --> 29:55.334
I thought you might
want to come with me.

29:55.419 --> 29:57.503
I'm your wife. Have we met?

29:57.588 --> 29:59.380
Would you really rather
stay here all day?

29:59.464 --> 30:02.008
Yes,
given the alternative.

30:02.092 --> 30:06.512
When I walk out in the morning,
all the street kids smile at me.

30:06.597 --> 30:08.389
That's 'cause
you give them money.

30:08.473 --> 30:09.932
Um, okay.

30:10.934 --> 30:12.435
I'll go on my own.

30:16.190 --> 30:18.900
[Children Cheering,
Chattering]

30:26.450 --> 30:29.869
- This can't be right, surely.
- I am thinking so, saab.

30:29.953 --> 30:32.830
There used to be
houses all along there.
These were homes.

30:32.915 --> 30:34.999
I can take you
some other place?

30:35.626 --> 30:38.169
No. No, no, no. No.

30:38.253 --> 30:40.671
That will be all for now.
Thank you.

30:40.797 --> 30:43.090
Here. Thank you very much.
Thank you, sir.

30:46.345 --> 30:49.764
Um, excuse me.
Yeah?

30:49.848 --> 30:53.643
- Uh, there used to be
houses here.
- All knocked down.

30:55.354 --> 30:57.813
What about the people,
the families?

30:57.898 --> 31:00.608
They moved to
a different place.

31:06.573 --> 31:10.534
Uh, don't...
don't grip it so tightly
with your right hand.

31:10.619 --> 31:11.869
The bat.

31:11.954 --> 31:13.496
Yes, it's just there
for guidance.

31:13.580 --> 31:15.998
You keep
your left elbow high...

31:16.083 --> 31:18.626
so you play through the ball.

31:18.752 --> 31:20.544
Thank you.
Okay.

31:33.684 --> 31:36.394
You're ready to go home,
Mrs. Donnelly.

31:36.478 --> 31:38.479
That's not my home.

31:38.563 --> 31:40.564
I want to go back
to England.

31:40.649 --> 31:44.735
As soon as you can stand up
and walk onto the plane,
you can.

31:44.820 --> 31:47.196
Until then, I will assist
in your recuperation.

31:48.782 --> 31:50.658
How is the hip feeling?

31:53.161 --> 31:54.996
They must have got lucky.

31:55.914 --> 31:57.498
It's strange.

31:57.582 --> 32:00.543
The more operations
they perform,
the luckier they get.

32:27.362 --> 32:29.363
[Door Opens]
Oh.

32:29.448 --> 32:32.408
I didn't realize.
Um, sorry.

32:34.870 --> 32:36.203
Oh!

32:36.288 --> 32:38.122
Oh, I'm so sorry.

32:38.206 --> 32:39.498
I'm dreadfully sorry.

32:39.624 --> 32:41.542
Yes?
Sorry.

32:41.626 --> 32:43.711
I'm just looking
for this address.

32:46.214 --> 32:48.049
Yes.
Do you understand?

32:48.133 --> 32:49.759
Could you help me
find this place?

32:49.843 --> 32:51.344
Yes.

32:51.428 --> 32:55.556
Is that, yes,
you do understand or,
yes, you could help me?

32:55.682 --> 32:58.100
Yes. Yes.
Oh.

32:58.185 --> 33:00.603
Well, let's just
go with both, shall we?

33:00.687 --> 33:01.937
Yes.

33:05.650 --> 33:07.735
[Chattering]

33:09.905 --> 33:11.405
Oh!

33:21.625 --> 33:23.751
[All Shouting]

33:23.835 --> 33:25.544
[Chuckles]
Yes.

33:25.629 --> 33:28.923
[Chuckling]

33:32.844 --> 33:34.804
[Coughs]

33:34.888 --> 33:36.597
Give me the ball.

33:36.723 --> 33:39.475
I can take him.
[Boys Shouting]

33:39.559 --> 33:42.561
Down is where
you are going, uncle.

33:42.646 --> 33:44.313
You do your worst.

33:44.398 --> 33:46.440
[All Chattering]

33:53.490 --> 33:54.990
Come on, Sanjay.
You can do it.

33:55.075 --> 33:56.534
Come on, Sanjay.

34:05.961 --> 34:08.879
[Shouts]

34:08.964 --> 34:12.425
I felt the need,
the need for speed.

34:12.509 --> 34:13.759
Yes!

34:17.013 --> 34:18.973
Are you all right, uncle?

34:20.266 --> 34:22.476
Yes. Yes, I'm fine.

34:35.614 --> 34:37.116
Oh.

34:40.078 --> 34:43.289
[Chattering]

34:43.373 --> 34:46.542
We do appreciate your custom,
which is very important to us.

34:46.626 --> 34:49.503
And can I draw your attention
to our special new...

34:50.964 --> 34:52.672
[Clicks]

34:57.220 --> 34:59.305
Are you sure I can't
offer you something?

34:59.389 --> 35:02.975
We have some, uh,
English breakfast tea.
Building tea, as you call it.

35:03.059 --> 35:05.561
A builder's tea?
Builder's tea.

35:05.645 --> 35:07.104
No, thank you. I'm fine.

35:07.189 --> 35:08.814
So, tell me. How can I help you?

35:08.899 --> 35:12.026
I don't think you can.
I'm sorry.
I shouldn't have come.

35:12.110 --> 35:13.527
No, wait.

35:13.612 --> 35:15.988
It's just that
I saw your advertisement
in the local newspaper,

35:16.072 --> 35:19.200
and it specifically mentioned
the ability to talk
to older people.

35:19.284 --> 35:22.703
But this wasn't
what I imagined.

35:22.787 --> 35:25.331
- You came for a job?
- I'm sorry.
I've wasted your time.

35:25.415 --> 35:29.793
Look, everyone working here
is a graduate
from a good university.

35:29.878 --> 35:33.047
This is a place
for ambitious people,
young people.

35:33.131 --> 35:34.715
Yes, I see that now.
I'm sorry.

35:34.799 --> 35:36.509
No. Please, sit down.

35:36.593 --> 35:38.802
Sit down. Please.

35:42.641 --> 35:44.391
So it is really builder's tea?

35:45.393 --> 35:48.771
Yes. We dunk biscuits
into it.

35:48.855 --> 35:50.356
You "dunk"?

35:51.942 --> 35:55.110
Well, it means
lowering the biscuit
into the tea...

35:55.195 --> 35:57.488
and letting it
soak in there...

35:57.572 --> 36:01.075
and trying to calculate
the exact moment before
the biscuit dissolves...

36:01.159 --> 36:03.369
when you can whip it up
into your mouth...

36:03.453 --> 36:06.789
and enjoy the blissful union
of biscuit and tea combined.

36:09.334 --> 36:10.960
It is more relaxing
than it sounds.

36:12.796 --> 36:14.755
Perhaps you can
help us after all.

36:14.839 --> 36:17.758
[Motorcycle Engine Revving]

36:21.388 --> 36:23.931
[Bell Rings]

36:25.100 --> 36:26.767
I thought
you weren't coming.

36:26.851 --> 36:28.519
[Chuckles]
Have I ever let you down?

36:28.603 --> 36:31.146
Um...
Don't answer that.

36:31.231 --> 36:33.357
[Bell Rings]

36:33.441 --> 36:34.733
I have to go.

36:34.818 --> 36:36.485
Leave this place.
Come to work for me.

36:36.570 --> 36:38.320
You can't afford me.

36:38.405 --> 36:39.947
I can't afford anything.

36:40.031 --> 36:41.156
I miss you.

36:41.241 --> 36:43.117
Am I coming round tonight?

36:43.201 --> 36:46.328
Uh, let's meet somewhere else.
I will rent a hotel room.

36:46.413 --> 36:49.373
Sonny, you own a hotel.
It has many rooms.

36:49.457 --> 36:53.335
Some of which are now occupied
with actual real guests.

36:53.420 --> 36:55.129
Paying guests?

36:55.213 --> 36:58.132
Why must you nitpick?
It is not an attractive quality.

37:01.344 --> 37:02.469
Sunaina.

37:04.055 --> 37:05.514
Hello, Jay.

37:05.599 --> 37:06.724
Sonny boy.

37:06.808 --> 37:08.559
Don't call me that.

37:08.643 --> 37:11.604
If you're gonna mess around
with my sister,
don't do it in public.

37:12.105 --> 37:13.480
Let's go.

37:30.206 --> 37:31.874
Good evening, Your Honor.

37:33.335 --> 37:36.211
Ah, good evening, Mrs. Ainslie.
You have a good day?

37:36.296 --> 37:38.172
What did you get up to?

37:38.256 --> 37:40.341
Well, I started
in my bedroom,

37:40.425 --> 37:43.719
where I spent a happy
couple of hours giving
all the cockroaches names.

37:43.803 --> 37:48.057
And then,
after a lunch that will long
have a place in my heartburn,

37:48.141 --> 37:50.768
I came out here
and stared blindly at a book,

37:50.852 --> 37:53.896
waiting for someone...
anyone... to rescue me.

37:55.190 --> 37:58.067
And how glad I am
it was you.

37:58.151 --> 38:00.527
Why would you not go out?
There's so much to see.

38:01.780 --> 38:04.740
All life is here, Mrs. Ainslie.
I tell you.

38:07.577 --> 38:10.037
Oh, I could have a word
with the chef if you like.

38:10.121 --> 38:13.165
Perhaps some grilled chicken
and plain rice?

38:13.249 --> 38:15.250
That would be
much appreciated.

38:16.378 --> 38:17.419
All right.

38:29.808 --> 38:32.059
[Insects Chirping]

38:54.541 --> 38:55.999
[Graham]
Good evening.

38:56.084 --> 38:57.251
Good evening.

38:57.377 --> 39:00.045
Please. Please, sit down.
Oh.

39:00.130 --> 39:01.130
Thank you.

39:01.214 --> 39:03.048
I trust you had
a good day.

39:03.133 --> 39:05.259
I'd rather hear about yours.

39:05.343 --> 39:08.262
I got a job...
my first ever.

39:08.346 --> 39:10.681
I'm going to be a sort of
cultural adviser.

39:10.765 --> 39:14.518
A role I'm sure you'll perform
with great distinction.

39:14.602 --> 39:17.438
[Chuckles]
Perhaps you wouldn't mind
keeping that to yourself.

39:17.522 --> 39:20.524
Well, I-I-I'm flattered
you told me about it.

39:20.608 --> 39:22.025
Good evening, the Ainslies.

39:22.152 --> 39:24.862
Did you have a good day?
Spectacular actually.

39:24.988 --> 39:29.199
I went to the temple
you told me about,
a place of meditation and peace.

39:29.284 --> 39:30.951
It was quite stunning.

39:31.035 --> 39:33.829
So spiritual,
I bet you never noticed
the smell of elephant dung.

39:33.913 --> 39:36.707
- [Chuckles]
- [Douglas]
No elephants, sadly.

39:36.791 --> 39:39.168
I thought I might
see you there. Where did you
get to instead?

39:39.252 --> 39:41.462
Yes, where do you
get to every day?

39:41.546 --> 39:44.381
Well, I-I've just been telling
Mrs. Greenslade all about it.

39:44.466 --> 39:46.216
[Jean]
I'm sure she wouldn't mind
hearing it again.

39:46.301 --> 39:50.137
Oh, I talked
to the chef for you.
Absolutely no problem.

39:50.221 --> 39:51.889
[Jean]
Did you hear that, Douglas?

39:51.973 --> 39:54.683
Plain grilled food.
Manna from heaven.

39:54.809 --> 39:57.770
I don't have to
have it too, do I?
I can't thank you enough.

39:57.854 --> 39:59.563
You really should
see this temple.

39:59.647 --> 40:01.273
Oh, I'd like to very much.

40:01.357 --> 40:03.859
But maybe take
a clothes-peg for your nose.

40:03.943 --> 40:05.736
[Chuckles]

40:07.030 --> 40:09.364
[Crickets Chirping]

40:09.491 --> 40:11.658
Good night.
Good night.

40:14.245 --> 40:15.913
Um, Mrs. Greenslade?

40:17.040 --> 40:18.499
Evelyn.

40:20.043 --> 40:22.711
Would you mind
if I showed you something?

40:24.589 --> 40:27.382
[Graham]
I grew up here,
just a short drive away.

40:28.676 --> 40:31.094
It was a big house.
We had servants.

40:31.179 --> 40:34.306
Oh, we knew their wives
and children, and...

40:34.390 --> 40:37.601
one of the boys, uh, Manoj...

40:37.685 --> 40:39.228
Oh.

40:41.314 --> 40:43.190
He, um...
He became my friend.

40:44.484 --> 40:47.861
And, uh, we played
lots of cricket together,
and...

40:47.946 --> 40:52.866
Well, we played everything
together, and-and it stayed
like that for a few years.

40:52.951 --> 40:54.159
And then, um...

40:55.119 --> 40:58.121
And then one night, it, uh...

40:58.206 --> 41:01.041
it became something else.

41:04.045 --> 41:06.129
We had
a few months together.
We had that.

41:06.214 --> 41:09.424
And, um...
And then there was
a weekend in Udaipur...

41:09.509 --> 41:15.180
where... we were sitting
by a lake and watching
the sun go down.

41:15.265 --> 41:20.310
And, uh, I remember
thinking that I-I would
never be this happy again.

41:20.395 --> 41:22.396
[Chuckles]

41:22.480 --> 41:26.108
And... And I was right.

41:26.192 --> 41:28.861
Because, suddenly,
it was over.

41:28.945 --> 41:32.239
We'd fallen asleep,
and they found us.

41:33.992 --> 41:36.159
Well, it was bad enough
for me.

41:36.244 --> 41:39.496
But I knew who I was,
and I think
my family guessed.

41:39.581 --> 41:41.331
But for...

41:41.416 --> 41:46.670
for Manoj, the...
the disgrace was absolute.

41:46.754 --> 41:50.299
His father was fired.
His family was sent away,
all of them.

41:52.844 --> 41:55.053
And, uh,

41:55.138 --> 41:57.139
well, I don't know
what I could have done.

41:57.223 --> 41:59.933
But it should have been
more than nothing.

42:00.018 --> 42:03.103
I just-
I just let it happen.

42:03.187 --> 42:07.107
I didn't put up
any kind of a fight. I...

42:09.027 --> 42:11.111
And then, um...

42:11.195 --> 42:13.906
Then I went back to England,
to-to-to university.

42:14.032 --> 42:19.953
And, uh, I always said,
you know, I'm going to go back.
I shall go back.

42:22.206 --> 42:24.583
And I never did.

42:25.501 --> 42:31.131
Until now.

42:32.508 --> 42:34.593
And now I think...

42:36.304 --> 42:40.140
What if I'm the last person
in the world
that he wants to see?

42:41.851 --> 42:44.478
Do you want to see him?
Yes.

42:47.023 --> 42:49.024
Yes, yes.

42:49.943 --> 42:52.069
Then you must.

42:54.155 --> 42:57.366
♪♪ [Indian Folk]
♪♪ [Man Vocalizing]

43:23.977 --> 43:26.979
♪♪ [Continues]

43:42.578 --> 43:45.580
♪♪ [Continues]
♪♪ [Singing
In Indian Language]

43:47.250 --> 43:49.876
[Sonny]
So now that we are fully
operational, Mr. Maruthi,

43:50.003 --> 43:53.588
it is clear that,
with a small injection of funds
for the phase two development,

43:53.673 --> 43:57.718
The Best Exotic Marigold Hotel
can rise like a phoenix...

43:57.802 --> 43:59.845
to its previous state of glory.

43:59.929 --> 44:02.431
And, look,
when I say small injection,

44:02.515 --> 44:05.392
I mean small
in the sense of,
uh, medium-sized.

44:05.476 --> 44:10.522
- Possibly larger.
- Well, this hotel
was never glorious.

44:10.606 --> 44:12.941
Just the phoenix part then.

44:13.067 --> 44:15.318
How many rooms
will there be?
Many. Mmm.

44:15.403 --> 44:17.112
How many?
A great amount.

44:17.196 --> 44:18.822
Plenty of rooms.
No question.

44:18.948 --> 44:21.908
I'm not a details man,
Mr. Maruthi.
Nor was your father.

44:21.993 --> 44:25.662
Mr. Maruthi,
I present to you
one of our beloved guests.

44:25.747 --> 44:27.247
Dear Mrs. Donnelly,

44:27.331 --> 44:30.709
please can you describe to us
in as much detail
as you desire...

44:30.793 --> 44:34.296
your experience
of the ambience
and atmosphere...

44:34.380 --> 44:36.965
of The Best Exotic
Marigold Hotel.

44:38.718 --> 44:40.218
Words fail me.

44:42.138 --> 44:44.222
[Laughs]

44:44.307 --> 44:48.226
Ah, the English wit
we love so greatly.

44:48.311 --> 44:49.811
Thank you, madam.

44:49.896 --> 44:54.274
See, the wheel is spinning,
but, you know,
the hamster is dead.

44:54.358 --> 44:58.487
- Mummyji,
what are you doing here?
- You called. I came.

44:58.571 --> 45:00.822
No, I couldn't have called.
The phones don't work.

45:00.907 --> 45:04.076
That's why I came.
[Speaks Hindi]

45:06.037 --> 45:09.706
- Wait! Mummyji,
this is my office!
- Who is that man out there?

45:09.791 --> 45:12.334
The contents
of that desk are mine.
Do not open the drawers.

45:12.418 --> 45:15.003
I must insist that you
do not open the drawers.

45:15.088 --> 45:16.379
Tell me.
Why have you come?

45:16.464 --> 45:18.548
Do I need a reason
to visit my favorite son?

45:18.674 --> 45:22.010
No. He's in his
mansion in Delhi.
All right. My second favorite.

45:22.095 --> 45:23.678
He went to Canada
to make his fortune.

45:23.763 --> 45:27.057
- And make it, he did.
- As I will make mine!

45:27.141 --> 45:30.018
I have a dream, Mummyji.
A most brilliant one.

45:30.103 --> 45:33.146
To outsource old age.
And it is not
just for the British.

45:33.272 --> 45:36.274
There are many other countries
where they don't
like old people too.

45:36.359 --> 45:39.694
Sonny, your brothers
own one-third
of this hotel each.

45:39.779 --> 45:42.405
They're also entitled
to one-third
of the profits, no?

45:42.490 --> 45:45.742
Success does not
happen overnight, Mummyji.

45:45.868 --> 45:50.997
This is blue-sky thinking,
and it requires long-term strategy
and-and-and patience.

45:51.082 --> 45:53.375
How is your girlfriend?

45:53.459 --> 45:55.168
I look forward
to you meeting her.

45:55.253 --> 45:57.963
And I look forward
to your meeting the girl
you're going to marry.

45:58.047 --> 46:01.049
She comes from
a very good family in Delhi,
beta, a very good family.

46:01.134 --> 46:04.511
I can marry as I choose,
Mummyji. I don't need
anyone's permission.

46:04.595 --> 46:08.390
I presume it is your girlfriend
who fills your head
with this nonsense, huh?

46:08.474 --> 46:10.809
A very good reason
not to marry her.

46:10.935 --> 46:14.020
What if I love her?
An even better reason.

46:14.105 --> 46:16.898
Now go and get Young Wasim
to come and get my luggage
from the car.

46:16.983 --> 46:20.944
He cannot carry.
He has a dicky back.
Wait. Your luggage?

46:21.070 --> 46:24.781
How long are you staying?
As long as it takes.

46:34.584 --> 46:37.836
Dear, you won't get anywhere
sweeping like that.

46:37.920 --> 46:42.007
I was in service for years.
Looked after a lovely house.

46:42.091 --> 46:46.386
Kept it spotless.
You need to put
more pressure on the brush.

46:46.470 --> 46:48.638
She won't speak English.

46:48.723 --> 46:50.932
She's what they used to call
an untouchable.

46:51.017 --> 46:53.727
To a good Hindu,
even her shadow is polluted.

46:54.437 --> 46:55.478
Namaste...

46:55.563 --> 46:58.023
[Speaking Indian Language]

47:00.693 --> 47:04.821
Where do you go every day?
Is it a woman?

47:04.906 --> 47:07.365
Go for a curry?
Have a bit of afters?

47:07.450 --> 47:08.950
[Both Chuckle]

47:09.035 --> 47:10.702
No, no, no. I don't think so.

47:10.786 --> 47:12.287
I'm, um...

47:12.371 --> 47:14.122
I'm gay. Uh...

47:14.207 --> 47:17.584
Though nowadays,
more in theory than in practice.

47:17.668 --> 47:19.544
But I-I-I'll see you later.

47:29.847 --> 47:31.681
[Exhales]

47:43.277 --> 47:46.863
[Man] The Viceroy Club
was opened by the great
Lord Kitchener himself,

47:46.948 --> 47:50.116
and many of its fixtures
have remained
unchanged since then.

47:50.201 --> 47:52.285
[Madge]
Yes, I see that.

47:52.370 --> 47:54.621
Perhaps you could tell me
a little about
the clientele.

47:55.790 --> 47:59.459
Any maharajas,
wealthy widowed
landowners?

47:59.543 --> 48:03.755
It is not the policy
of this club to divulge details
of our members, madam.

48:03.839 --> 48:06.633
- Good morning, Your Excellency.
- Very good morning.

48:08.135 --> 48:09.427
Where do I sign up?

48:09.512 --> 48:12.264
The admission fee
is 120,000 rupees,

48:12.348 --> 48:16.017
and, thereafter, it will be
15,000 rupees each month.

48:16.102 --> 48:20.480
I wonder if I might
get a little discount,
owing to my status.

48:20.564 --> 48:22.023
Your status, madam?

48:22.108 --> 48:24.734
Yes. One was rather hoping
to fly under the radar,

48:24.819 --> 48:26.861
but one is a member
of the royal family.

48:26.988 --> 48:29.531
Which member, madam?
I'm Princess Margaret.

48:31.284 --> 48:33.576
It is most certainly
an honor to meet you, madam.

48:33.661 --> 48:36.121
And may I say
how well you look,

48:36.205 --> 48:38.665
especially taking into account
that you died nine years ago.

48:40.001 --> 48:43.962
Your real name please, madam,
and 120,000 rupees.

48:53.889 --> 48:56.016
[Jean]
You know where he goes.

48:57.935 --> 49:00.645
I know you know,
but you won't tell me.

49:02.398 --> 49:05.567
I can get Hobnobs out here,
you know. I know a way.

49:07.236 --> 49:09.321
As many as you like.

49:09.405 --> 49:11.239
Milk or plain.

49:14.952 --> 49:16.911
Public records office.

49:19.165 --> 49:21.833
[Boys Shouting]

49:24.295 --> 49:26.254
[Sonny]
My mother doesn't want us
to be married.

49:26.380 --> 49:29.466
[Sunaina]
She hasn't met me yet.
She doesn't need to meet you.

49:29.550 --> 49:31.134
She knows you're
not from Delhi,

49:31.218 --> 49:34.596
that you have no family money,
and you work in a call center.

49:34.680 --> 49:37.766
You're part of a modern India
she cannot welcome.

49:37.892 --> 49:40.477
Then you must tell her
what you want.
I'm trying.

49:40.561 --> 49:41.686
Try harder.

49:44.148 --> 49:45.899
Do you love me, Sonny?

49:45.983 --> 49:48.818
My feelings for you
cannot be reduced
to a single word.

49:48.903 --> 49:52.322
It's a nice word.
People like hearing it.

49:52.406 --> 49:56.451
You know, it will be easier
to talk to my mother
when the hotel is a success.

49:56.535 --> 49:58.078
And what if it isn't?

49:58.162 --> 50:00.622
Everything will be
all right in the end.

50:00.706 --> 50:03.291
And if it is not all right,
then it is not yet the end.

50:03.417 --> 50:05.752
Sonny!
It will succeed.

50:06.796 --> 50:08.838
It has to.

50:08.923 --> 50:11.091
Because then you can
stand up to your family?

50:12.093 --> 50:14.552
Because then
I can stand next to you.

50:16.138 --> 50:18.640
[Chattering In Hindi]

50:21.060 --> 50:23.645
Are you all right,
auntie?

50:23.729 --> 50:27.816
Uh, yes. I'm about to make
the first public speech
of my life.

50:27.900 --> 50:29.609
[Chuckles]

50:31.153 --> 50:34.656
Imagine them naked.
Sorry?

50:34.740 --> 50:37.325
It's the way not to be scared
when speaking in public.

50:37.410 --> 50:39.077
You imagine people naked.

50:39.161 --> 50:41.454
Well, I'm afraid I gave that up
several years ago.

50:46.794 --> 50:48.336
Let's see.

50:50.923 --> 50:52.590
Oh, dear.

51:07.106 --> 51:11.526
Excuse me. Would there be
any wealthy single men in
this evening?

51:11.610 --> 51:14.571
Uh, there is one.

51:14.655 --> 51:16.698
Perhaps you could
seat me next to him.

51:16.782 --> 51:19.284
[Chuckles]
This way, madam.

51:27.543 --> 51:30.211
His Royal Highness,
Prince Michael of Kent.

51:38.220 --> 51:41.014
I'll have that back.
Thank you very much.

51:44.560 --> 51:45.935
Ready?
[Sunaina]
Yes.

51:46.020 --> 51:48.563
- Ring me up.
- Ring you up...

51:48.647 --> 51:52.358
As you would.
You know, dial my number.

51:55.738 --> 51:57.614
It's ringing.
Hello.

51:57.698 --> 51:59.949
Good morning, madam.
And how are you today?

52:00.034 --> 52:04.078
Oh, no.
That won't do for a start.
That's much too nursie.

52:04.163 --> 52:06.748
- I feel as if
I'm on my deathbed.
- [All Chuckle]

52:06.832 --> 52:09.584
If I could just take
a few moments of your time
to tell you about-

52:09.668 --> 52:11.628
How long
will you actually take?

52:11.754 --> 52:13.922
Twelve minutes.
Then you've lied
to me already.

52:14.006 --> 52:16.549
No, I can't talk to you.
I'm watching TV.

52:16.634 --> 52:18.510
Why does she need
12 minutes?

52:18.594 --> 52:21.304
Well, we believe
the longer we keep
our customers on the phone,

52:21.388 --> 52:24.474
the more receptive
they'll be to our message.

52:24.558 --> 52:26.559
It's my favorite program.

52:26.644 --> 52:28.770
Yes, but I really think
if you heard
some of our special...

52:28.854 --> 52:32.524
No, no.
Don't talk like a robot.
Now just talk to me.

52:32.608 --> 52:34.275
You've heard
I'm watching TV.

52:34.360 --> 52:36.778
- What are you watching?
- Oh, a marvelous program...

52:36.862 --> 52:39.364
where a chap talks to
a panel of young women...

52:39.448 --> 52:41.533
whose boyfriends
have all slept
with their mothers.

52:41.617 --> 52:42.784
[All Chuckle]

52:42.868 --> 52:44.452
Well, the girlfriends' mothers,
I mean, not-

52:44.578 --> 52:46.162
[All Chuckle]
Although...

52:46.288 --> 52:50.667
- [Chuckles]
- Anyway, the boys have come on,
and everybody's fighting.

52:50.751 --> 52:53.086
It sounds amazing.
Hang up right now.

52:54.296 --> 52:58.508
- I'm Sunaina.
- Good. Now that's very good.

52:58.592 --> 52:59.884
Evelyn. Evelyn.

52:59.969 --> 53:01.803
Now can I speak to you
about our special offers?

53:01.887 --> 53:04.806
Still too soon.
I obviously want to talk.

53:04.890 --> 53:06.599
Is your husband watching
with you, Evelyn?

53:08.644 --> 53:11.521
No. No, he died.

53:14.608 --> 53:16.109
Um, perhaps you...

53:16.193 --> 53:18.570
You know,
I've actually had
a version of this call.

53:18.654 --> 53:24.867
A little while ago,
I talked to someone who was
so constricted by the scripts,

53:24.952 --> 53:27.078
well, sales agenda,

53:27.162 --> 53:30.206
that she spoke
without a trace of humanity.

53:31.458 --> 53:33.710
As if she hadn't
realized that...

53:33.794 --> 53:37.130
I was going
completely to pieces
at the end of the phone.

53:41.385 --> 53:43.177
You must miss him very much.

53:45.973 --> 53:49.434
Now, sympathy's fine.
But be more optimistic.

53:51.270 --> 53:55.773
Um, but, you know, sometimes
I find when one door closes...

53:55.858 --> 53:59.193
- The rest of them
stay shut as well.
- [All Chuckle]

53:59.278 --> 54:02.780
No, you're right.
Of course you're right.
It's a new beginning.

54:02.865 --> 54:05.617
Now what do you want
to talk to me about?

54:05.743 --> 54:07.327
There.
Three minutes?

54:07.453 --> 54:10.997
Well, either
I've saved you nine,
or I've talked myself out of a job.

54:11.081 --> 54:12.498
[All Chuckle]

54:12.666 --> 54:15.710
I still think
you're cramping my style.

54:15.794 --> 54:17.879
Oh, please.
You have no style to cramp.

54:17.963 --> 54:20.423
That lady at the bar
keeps looking at me.

54:21.467 --> 54:24.010
As one would
something in a museum.

54:24.094 --> 54:26.095
Why must you mock?

54:26.180 --> 54:27.972
I just want to
feel young again.

54:28.057 --> 54:33.686
To feel needed
as much as I need,
if only for one night.

54:33.771 --> 54:38.274
One wonderful night.

54:39.985 --> 54:42.195
Tell me you don't know
how that feels.

54:44.531 --> 54:47.325
Give me a minute
and then come and join me.

54:52.498 --> 54:54.290
[Sighs]

54:54.375 --> 54:56.417
Rejected again.

54:58.420 --> 55:03.424
Many years ago that man
over there gave me the most
extraordinary night of my life.

55:04.968 --> 55:08.221
To describe his bedroom skill
as technique would...

55:08.305 --> 55:12.016
- Those drinks not ready yet?
- They say patience
is passion tamed.

55:12.101 --> 55:14.560
- I'm Madge.
- Carol.

55:14.687 --> 55:17.230
And this is Norman.
How do you do?

55:17.314 --> 55:20.400
Carol. As in Christmas.

55:20.484 --> 55:23.069
- I suppose.
- Great.

55:23.153 --> 55:25.279
So what brings you
to Jaipur, Carol?

55:25.364 --> 55:28.157
Yes, Carol. What, uh...
What brings you to Jaipur?

55:28.242 --> 55:32.245
Actually, I've lived here
all my life. My father
worked for the foreign office.

55:34.748 --> 55:36.457
- You're very fit.
- Beg your pardon?

55:36.583 --> 55:41.421
- Oh, God.
- You look like you keep yourself
in good shape, physically.

55:41.505 --> 55:45.675
Well...
[Clears Throat]
I did join a gym last year.

55:45.759 --> 55:48.720
It cost a fortune,
and I didn't get any fitter.

55:48.804 --> 55:51.431
- Apparently,
you actually have to go.
- [Chuckles]

55:53.100 --> 55:55.059
Ah!
[Chuckles]

55:58.981 --> 56:03.401
So, um,
what do you do, Norman?

56:03.485 --> 56:04.610
- Me?
- Yes.

56:04.737 --> 56:06.279
Norman's in business.
Well, I... Yes.

56:06.363 --> 56:07.697
- What business?
- You tell her.

56:07.781 --> 56:09.031
Import-export.

56:09.116 --> 56:11.743
Although nowadays,
there's rather more
"ex" than "im."

56:11.827 --> 56:15.037
- If you know what I mean.
- No, I'm afraid I don't.

56:16.915 --> 56:19.917
I have to go
and splash some water
on my face.

56:20.002 --> 56:21.836
Please, God,
I drown in it.

56:29.428 --> 56:32.555
Well, look.
It's been lovely chatting.
No, it hasn't.

56:32.639 --> 56:34.640
No, it hasn't.
But I really have to go.

56:34.725 --> 56:37.268
Look, Carol, Carol.

56:38.687 --> 56:41.522
Can we drop
all this pretense?

56:41.607 --> 56:44.275
Start again?

56:44.359 --> 56:47.153
I'm not charming.
I'm not good at repartee.
And...

56:50.574 --> 56:55.036
My name's Norman,
and I'm lonely.

56:56.163 --> 56:59.415
My name's Carol. So am I.

57:03.212 --> 57:04.587
[Chuckles]

57:06.298 --> 57:08.716
[Chattering]

57:10.177 --> 57:12.261
[Evelyn Narrating]
Day 22.

57:12.346 --> 57:17.517
Like Darwin's finches,
we are slowly adapting
to our environment.

57:19.436 --> 57:21.229
And when one does adapt,

57:21.313 --> 57:24.524
my God,
the riches that are available.

57:33.784 --> 57:37.703
There is no past
that we can bring back
by longing for it.

57:37.788 --> 57:42.375
Only a present that builds
and creates itself
as the past withdraws.

57:45.420 --> 57:48.256
Didn't sleep a wink last night.
The tap in there
never stopped dripping.

57:48.340 --> 57:51.050
Ah. I spoke to Young Wasim
about that.

57:51.134 --> 57:53.845
- What did he say?
- No idea. It was in Hindi.

57:56.682 --> 57:59.809
- I thought I might
fix it myself.
- You? When?

57:59.893 --> 58:02.228
Well, no time
like the present.

58:05.899 --> 58:08.901
Where is this? Where are we?

58:09.027 --> 58:11.112
Janta Colony, Kachchi Basti.
[Gasps]

58:12.155 --> 58:14.699
Well, what happened
to my usual route?

58:14.783 --> 58:16.450
Anokhi has invited you
to her home.

58:17.911 --> 58:20.121
Who's Anokhi?

58:20.205 --> 58:22.123
The one who brings
your food.

58:22.207 --> 58:24.250
She wants you to meet
her family.

58:37.931 --> 58:39.932
[Chattering]

58:42.728 --> 58:44.437
How soon can I leave?

58:44.521 --> 58:47.773
[Anokhi Speaking
Indian Language]

58:54.281 --> 58:56.282
She wants to thank you
for your kindness.

58:57.075 --> 58:59.285
I haven't been kind.

58:59.369 --> 59:01.287
You are the only one
that acknowledges her.

59:13.550 --> 59:15.468
[Indian Language]

59:20.933 --> 59:22.433
I'm not eating that.

59:22.517 --> 59:24.977
You will insult her
very deeply if you do not.

59:43.246 --> 59:44.705
It's good.

59:46.375 --> 59:48.334
[Chuckles]

59:49.378 --> 59:52.046
- Oh!
[Chuckles]
- [Metal Clanks]

59:52.130 --> 59:55.257
Get off there!
The little bastards!
Get off!

59:55.342 --> 59:57.385
Get up! Get 'em off there!

59:57.469 --> 59:59.387
Get 'em off me...

01:00:02.891 --> 01:00:04.392
Ah.

01:00:05.185 --> 01:00:06.811
I... I di...

01:00:08.772 --> 01:00:10.815
I didn't know
they were playing. I...
[Chuckles]

01:00:13.068 --> 01:00:14.110
Sorry.

01:00:17.322 --> 01:00:19.198
I'm sorry.

01:00:22.828 --> 01:00:23.869
Sorry.

01:00:29.376 --> 01:00:31.711
How much for this piece?

01:00:31.795 --> 01:00:34.338
One thousand rupees.
[Speaks Hindi]

01:00:34.423 --> 01:00:36.090
Thank you.
No, no, no, no.

01:00:36.174 --> 01:00:40.386
Forgive me. Forgive me.
No, no. That's, um...
That's not how it works.

01:00:40.470 --> 01:00:42.221
Uh, sorry to butt in.

01:00:42.347 --> 01:00:45.641
But, uh, you don't ask him
how much he wants.
You just tell him how much you'll pay.

01:00:45.767 --> 01:00:51.814
She'll give you, uh...
She'll give you 200.
Absolutely no more, final offer.

01:00:51.898 --> 01:00:54.108
One thousand rupees.
Pity.

01:00:54.234 --> 01:00:56.277
Walk away. Now walk away.
Oh, but...

01:00:56.361 --> 01:00:58.070
I know what I'm doing.

01:00:58.155 --> 01:01:01.073
- The thing is
I really wanted to buy that.
- He'll come after us.

01:01:02.701 --> 01:01:04.285
Do you think so?
Absolutely.

01:01:04.369 --> 01:01:06.620
This is how
the game is played.
Just keep on walking.

01:01:08.165 --> 01:01:09.999
He's playing it very cool,
but he'll come.

01:01:10.083 --> 01:01:12.001
Ah.
[Chuckles]

01:01:12.085 --> 01:01:16.881
He's playing it
very, very, um, cool.

01:01:16.965 --> 01:01:21.802
850, 900, 950, 1,000.

01:01:21.928 --> 01:01:23.721
Thank you.
Sure.

01:01:23.805 --> 01:01:25.639
You'll get him next time.

01:01:26.641 --> 01:01:28.434
Why are you carrying a tap?

01:01:28.518 --> 01:01:31.604
You see, what I think,
and of course,
I'm no expert,

01:01:31.688 --> 01:01:35.649
is that the gland nut
has come away from
the spindle,

01:01:35.734 --> 01:01:38.194
so it needs to be
tightened and resealed.

01:01:42.491 --> 01:01:44.658
The washer valve has eroded.

01:01:44.743 --> 01:01:49.830
Yeah. Uh, well, uh, yeah.
It-It-It could be that too.

01:01:49.915 --> 01:01:53.584
- Um, uh, can you fix it?
- Not cheaply.

01:01:53.668 --> 01:01:56.796
Not cheaply.
Most expensively indeed.

01:02:00.967 --> 01:02:03.844
I was in a...
I was in a tuk-tuk
the other day.

01:02:03.929 --> 01:02:06.514
It didn't seem to be taking
the usual route
back to the hotel.

01:02:06.598 --> 01:02:09.558
It turned out
the driver had decided
to take me to another hotel...

01:02:09.684 --> 01:02:11.393
he was sure I'd prefer.
[Chuckles]

01:02:11.478 --> 01:02:13.896
[Chuckles]

01:02:14.022 --> 01:02:16.899
Of course, one wants to believe
that he genuinely
had my welfare at heart...

01:02:16.983 --> 01:02:19.485
and that it wasn't
run by his brother-in-law.

01:02:19.611 --> 01:02:23.906
[Chuckles]
One wants to trust in general,
don't you think?

01:02:23.990 --> 01:02:25.991
But you never really know.

01:02:26.076 --> 01:02:28.077
[Banging]

01:02:28.161 --> 01:02:31.664
I met my husband the day
the fair came to town.

01:02:31.748 --> 01:02:33.791
My girlfriend and I
went on the carousel.

01:02:33.875 --> 01:02:37.670
Her horse was fine,
but when the ride started,

01:02:37.754 --> 01:02:42.049
I felt mine give a little,
as if it might collapse.

01:02:42.134 --> 01:02:44.218
And then suddenly,
I felt these arms
around me,

01:02:44.302 --> 01:02:48.389
and a voice in my ear said,
"Just trust me," and I did.

01:02:48.473 --> 01:02:50.724
Without question,
till the day he died.

01:02:50.809 --> 01:02:53.018
[Hammering]

01:02:56.189 --> 01:02:57.857
How wonderful.

01:02:59.025 --> 01:03:01.235
The sale of our flat
went through last week.

01:03:01.319 --> 01:03:03.904
I had to sell it
to pay off Hugh's debts.

01:03:06.241 --> 01:03:09.702
I've been forced
to get a job out here,
which, in fact, I love.

01:03:11.079 --> 01:03:14.707
Because even
at Sonny's rates,
I couldn't make ends meet.

01:03:14.791 --> 01:03:18.460
Not after what happened
to our life savings.

01:03:18.545 --> 01:03:22.381
So, no, you're right.
You never know.

01:03:46.948 --> 01:03:48.532
[Chattering]

01:03:48.617 --> 01:03:50.326
Off you go then.
Excuse me.

01:03:50.410 --> 01:03:53.078
Off you go. Go home! Go, go!

01:04:19.397 --> 01:04:21.357
[Soft Chattering]
[Phone Rings]

01:04:21.483 --> 01:04:25.444
[Graham] But I've already
filled this form in.
I've given it to you, many times.

01:04:25.528 --> 01:04:27.363
[Man]
There is a process.

01:04:27.447 --> 01:04:31.200
You are making an inquiry,
and for each inquiry,
a form must be filled in.

01:04:31.284 --> 01:04:34.703
But it's the same inquiry
I make every day.

01:04:34.788 --> 01:04:37.790
And, therefore,
the same form you must fill in.

01:04:47.425 --> 01:04:49.343
Mrs. Ainslie.

01:04:52.806 --> 01:04:57.351
How can you bear this country?
What do you see that I don't?

01:04:58.478 --> 01:05:02.106
Oh, the light, colors.

01:05:02.190 --> 01:05:03.899
Smiles.

01:05:03.984 --> 01:05:06.402
[Chuckles]
And...

01:05:06.486 --> 01:05:10.781
And the way people see life
as a... as a... as a privilege
and-and not a right.

01:05:10.865 --> 01:05:12.533
It-It teaches me something.

01:05:15.036 --> 01:05:19.581
Is that milk pasteurized?
Yes, ma'am.
Very, very "posturized."

01:05:19.666 --> 01:05:22.626
But that's not true, is it?
You're lying to me
just now because...

01:05:22.711 --> 01:05:26.338
No, no. It'll be fine.
Thank you.

01:05:32.053 --> 01:05:35.055
It was a pleasant surprise
to see you out and about.

01:05:36.308 --> 01:05:39.184
Was it?
Yes, yes. It's progress,
I think.

01:05:40.562 --> 01:05:42.354
I was going to the bank.

01:05:44.107 --> 01:05:45.649
To the bank.

01:05:45.734 --> 01:05:48.152
Not that there's any reason
to think that
something has changed,

01:05:48.236 --> 01:05:50.362
but our daughter, Laura,
she did promise,

01:05:50.447 --> 01:05:53.532
and one tries to remain
optimistic.

01:05:53.616 --> 01:05:55.451
[Chuckles]

01:05:55.535 --> 01:06:00.456
Otherwise...

01:06:03.209 --> 01:06:06.086
Actually,
I wasn't going to the bank.
I was looking for you.

01:06:06.171 --> 01:06:10.174
In fact, I think
I've been looking for you
for a very long time.

01:06:10.300 --> 01:06:12.676
Mrs. Ainslie.
Jean.

01:06:13.803 --> 01:06:15.471
I'm gay.

01:06:19.768 --> 01:06:23.979
As in... happy?

01:06:27.650 --> 01:06:30.152
Yes, yes.
Yes, of course.
I see. I see.

01:06:34.407 --> 01:06:35.949
Thank you.

01:06:36.034 --> 01:06:37.618
What for?

01:06:38.953 --> 01:06:41.497
For averting
my complete humiliation.

01:06:44.376 --> 01:06:47.044
As I said,
this country's driving me mad.

01:06:49.798 --> 01:06:51.590
Shall we go?

01:06:52.634 --> 01:06:54.885
Anything?
[Douglas]
Not yet.

01:06:57.847 --> 01:06:59.807
- How about now?
- One second.

01:06:59.891 --> 01:07:02.393
[Water Running]

01:07:03.269 --> 01:07:04.812
Oh!
[Chuckles]

01:07:04.896 --> 01:07:06.772
- Good Lord!
- What?

01:07:06.856 --> 01:07:09.566
- Listen.
- [Water Running]

01:07:09.651 --> 01:07:11.610
And now...
[Water Stops]

01:07:12.737 --> 01:07:14.405
No drip!

01:07:14.489 --> 01:07:17.950
- Oh!
- [Laughing]

01:07:18.034 --> 01:07:20.411
No drip! High five.

01:07:20.495 --> 01:07:23.664
No, sorry. I don't know why
I did that. I've never
done it before in my life.

01:07:23.790 --> 01:07:25.916
Mrs. Ainslie.
Darling.

01:07:26.000 --> 01:07:28.961
How are you?
Did you have a good day?

01:07:29.045 --> 01:07:30.754
Well, let me tell you
about ours.

01:07:30.839 --> 01:07:32.172
Your husband of many a year,

01:07:32.257 --> 01:07:33.966
who's never known
which end of a hammer to use,

01:07:34.092 --> 01:07:36.385
has finally managed...
We have to get out of here.

01:07:36.469 --> 01:07:39.263
- What did you say?
- I can't stay in this country
a moment longer.

01:07:39.389 --> 01:07:40.806
[Douglas]
Why?
Excuse me.

01:07:40.890 --> 01:07:43.892
Pick a reason. Pick ten.
The climate, the squalor.

01:07:43.977 --> 01:07:45.936
The poverty.

01:07:46.020 --> 01:07:48.480
This whole trip
is a grotesque fantasy.

01:07:48.565 --> 01:07:51.024
- It's time we went home.
- Who's paying for the tickets?

01:07:51.109 --> 01:07:54.111
Look at us. A group
of self-deluding old fossils...

01:07:54.237 --> 01:07:58.907
traipsing around as if
we're on some bloody gap year,
humiliating ourselves.

01:07:59.033 --> 01:08:02.453
Not us. We couldn't pay.
And I don't see you
asking our friends back home.

01:08:02.537 --> 01:08:06.290
We should just face up to
the truth. That we're all old.
We're all past it.

01:08:06.374 --> 01:08:10.335
That's the real truth.
The raw, unvarnished fact
of the matter.

01:08:10.420 --> 01:08:14.423
All we're good for now
is a beige bloody bungalow.

01:08:14.507 --> 01:08:19.470
With a sodding panic button
in the... sodding corner.

01:08:22.098 --> 01:08:26.018
[Sobbing]

01:08:30.648 --> 01:08:33.484
We just have to make
the best of things, darling.

01:08:35.904 --> 01:08:40.282
I really think
that's the best thing to do.

01:08:41.783 --> 01:08:43.535
Yes, well!

01:08:45.246 --> 01:08:47.622
When I want your opinion,
I'll give it to you.

01:08:56.966 --> 01:09:00.844
♪♪ [Man Singing Prayer In Arabic]

01:09:12.273 --> 01:09:14.649
[Buzzing]

01:09:14.734 --> 01:09:16.859
[Crowd Chattering Softly]

01:09:16.944 --> 01:09:20.113
[Line Ringing]

01:09:20.198 --> 01:09:22.533
[Sonny]
Come on. Come on.
Pick up. Pick up.

01:09:22.658 --> 01:09:26.203
[Line Ringing]
Pick up. Pick up. Pick up.

01:09:26.287 --> 01:09:28.121
Well, in that case,
thank you for your call.

01:09:28.247 --> 01:09:31.291
I'll get back to you
as soon as I've discussed this
with my manager.

01:09:31.376 --> 01:09:33.417
Sunaina, I must see you.

01:09:33.502 --> 01:09:37.464
I must. If I cannot hold you
in my arms tonight,
I swear I will go mad.

01:09:37.549 --> 01:09:39.131
I yearn for you.

01:09:39.216 --> 01:09:40.551
I burn for you.

01:09:40.635 --> 01:09:43.636
I think it's my sister
you're burning for there,
Sonny boy.

01:09:43.720 --> 01:09:46.598
Thank you, Jay. Thank you.

01:09:47.725 --> 01:09:49.309
- Hey.
- Private line, Sunaina.

01:09:49.394 --> 01:09:51.144
Do those words mean
nothing to you?

01:09:51.229 --> 01:09:52.813
He took the phone.
What could I do?

01:09:52.897 --> 01:09:55.524
I miss you.

01:09:55.608 --> 01:09:59.278
I miss you every moment.
Come and see me. Tonight.

01:09:59.362 --> 01:10:03.240
I cannot tonight.
It's our parents'
25th wedding anniversary.

01:10:03.324 --> 01:10:05.659
- Tell your mother that.
- Come after. Come late.

01:10:05.785 --> 01:10:08.579
You will be asleep.
No, I'll be waiting.

01:10:08.663 --> 01:10:10.706
You'll be asleep.

01:10:10.790 --> 01:10:12.916
But I can wake you up
in that special way.

01:10:13.001 --> 01:10:15.419
- You'll sneak in?
- I'm not ashamed.

01:10:15.503 --> 01:10:17.421
No, no, no. Neither am I.
Absolutely not.

01:10:17.505 --> 01:10:20.549
There is no shame.
You don't have to sneak.

01:10:20.633 --> 01:10:24.136
Although, if you did
want to be very quiet
and not let anyone see,

01:10:24.220 --> 01:10:25.721
it couldn't hurt.

01:10:27.473 --> 01:10:28.974
Su... Sunaina?

01:10:36.566 --> 01:10:38.984
I wanted
to tell you something.

01:10:41.988 --> 01:10:44.781
Would you tell her
I was glad to come?

01:10:45.783 --> 01:10:47.701
Glad she invited me.

01:10:47.785 --> 01:10:51.663
[Indian Language]

01:10:54.792 --> 01:10:58.879
Glad to meet her family...
her grandmother and her kids.

01:10:58.963 --> 01:11:07.929
[Indian Language]

01:11:12.644 --> 01:11:14.728
She asks
if you have children.

01:11:18.566 --> 01:11:21.026
No, I looked after
somebody else's.

01:11:21.110 --> 01:11:23.654
[Indian Language]

01:11:23.738 --> 01:11:26.198
Just this one family.

01:11:26.282 --> 01:11:27.949
Years I was with 'em.

01:11:28.034 --> 01:11:30.869
[Indian Language]

01:11:30.953 --> 01:11:34.289
I ran the house.
Looked after the money,
did it all.

01:11:34.415 --> 01:11:37.292
Uh...
Cared for them
like they were my own.

01:11:37.377 --> 01:11:40.587
[Indian Language]

01:11:42.173 --> 01:11:46.551
One day, they decided
I needed some help.

01:11:46.678 --> 01:11:50.013
[Indian Language]
I was grateful.

01:11:50.098 --> 01:11:52.474
And they got this...
this young woman.

01:11:54.018 --> 01:11:56.520
And I tried to teach her.

01:11:56.604 --> 01:11:58.271
Not just the books.

01:11:58.356 --> 01:12:01.942
How to crisp up the bacon,
the way the gentleman
preferred it, you know.

01:12:02.026 --> 01:12:04.236
And how the little one liked
to have her hair brushed.

01:12:04.320 --> 01:12:06.863
Just, you know,
little things...

01:12:06.948 --> 01:12:08.865
you only know
if you really care.

01:12:09.867 --> 01:12:13.620
Well, I...
I must've done a good job.

01:12:15.790 --> 01:12:19.918
'Cause they said I was
no longer useful to them.

01:12:20.002 --> 01:12:22.629
They thanked me
for my service...

01:12:22.714 --> 01:12:24.798
as if that was all it was.

01:12:26.718 --> 01:12:31.888
I found, um, a flat in the end.

01:12:31.973 --> 01:12:38.186
My problem was what to do
with all the time I had.

01:12:38.271 --> 01:12:42.899
I mean, the flat-
It's so small, I can have it
spotless in half an hour.

01:12:44.068 --> 01:12:46.570
And then, you know,
what am I supposed to do?

01:12:47.321 --> 01:12:48.947
For the rest of the day?

01:12:52.410 --> 01:12:54.911
- Give her these, will you?
- Sure.

01:12:56.914 --> 01:12:58.874
[Indian Language]

01:13:07.675 --> 01:13:09.342
John Smith.

01:13:11.846 --> 01:13:13.972
Mr. John Smith.

01:13:14.807 --> 01:13:17.434
That's right. Me.

01:13:17.518 --> 01:13:19.394
Ah, this way.

